On this day in history in 1863, the Battle of Chickamauga ended in a Confederate victory. 

The Battle of Chickamauga occurred between the US Army of the Cumberland, led by Maj. Gen. William Rosecrans, and the Confederate Army of Tennessee, commanded by Gen. Braxton Bragg. Rosecrans aimed to drive the Confederates out of Chattanooga. In early September, he consolidated his forces and pushed Bragg's army south.

Bragg sought to retake Chattanooga, intending to strike Rosecrans’s isolated troops. A miscommunication led Rosecrans to create an actual gap in his defenses, which Confederate Lt. Gen. James Longstreet exploited, resulting in a rout of Union forces. The Union ultimately retreated to Chattanooga, while the Confederates took control of the surrounding heights, besieging the city.

This battle was notable as the first major conflict in Georgia and represented the largest Union defeat in the Western Theater, resulting in the second-highest number of casualties after Gettysburg.

On this day in history in 1995, the manifesto of Theodore Kaczynski, known as the Unabomber, was published by The New York Times and Washington Post to identify the individual responsible for a 17-year bombing campaign that killed three and injured 23. 

His bombing spree began in 1978, starting with an un-mailed package that injured a security guard. Over the next several years, Kaczynski mailed homemade pipe bombs to various targets, including executives at American and United Airlines and academic administrators, resulting in several injuries. The violence led to the death of a computer store owner in California. Ultimately, the Unabomber carried out 14 attacks with 16 bombs.

Kaczynski promised to halt his attacks if his manifesto was published in full by a major outlet. In his manifesto, Kaczynski contended that technology had distanced humans from nature. He advocated for a return to “wild nature,” arguing that this necessitated an end to all scientific research.

Kaczynski's brother, David, recognized the writing style as that of Ted, who was later convicted and sentenced to life in prison without parole. His capture ended the FBI’s longest and most expensive manhunt.

On this day in history in 1787, 39 delegates signed the Constitution of the United States of America. 

Today, on National Constitution Day, we honor the courage and vision of the men who drafted and signed this historic document—establishing the framework of a democratic republic and safeguarding our individual rights and liberties.

Before the Constitution, the country was governed under the Articles of Confederation, adopted prior to Britain’s surrender in 1781. The Articles created a loose confederation of states, granting Congress authority over foreign affairs, war, and currency, but denying it the power to enforce laws, raise funds, or compel troops, threatening the stability of the Union. A meeting in Annapolis paved the way for a Constitutional Convention in Philadelphia.

In 1787, delegates from every state but Rhode Island gathered in Philadelphia. George Washington was chosen to preside over the convention. The delegates drafted a new framework of government, based on federalism, separation of powers, and checks and balances.

The Constitution was signed on September 17, 1787, but it required ratification by nine states before taking effect. While five states quickly ratified, others—including Massachusetts—insisted on greater protections for individual liberties. 

Ratification was ultimately secured through a promise to adopt amendments addressing these concerns. That commitment gave rise to the Bill of Rights, the first ten amendments to the Constitution, ratified in 1791.

Tanks were designed to withstand gunfire, crush barbed wire, and cross wide trenches. To maintain secrecy, they were called “tanks” during development. The first models, known as Mark I or “Little Willies,” carried eight men and reached speeds of just under 4 mph.

On this day in history in 1940, four teens discovered prehistoric cave paintings dating back 15,000 to 17,000 years while exploring a cavern after their dog led them there. 

Found near Montignac, France, these paintings featured detailed depictions of animals. They are considered among the best examples of Upper Paleolithic art.

The Lascaux cave, studied by archaeologist Henri-Édouard-Prosper Breuil, features around 600 paintings and 1,500 engravings of animals and symbols, with one human figure. Used for hunting and religious practices, the cave was closed to the public in 1963 due to damage but is now replicated for visitors.

On this day in history in 2001, the largest terrorist attack in American history took place.

At 8:46 a.m., an American Airlines Boeing 767 crashed into the north tower of the World Trade Center in New York City, killing hundreds instantly and trapping many others. Seventeen minutes later, at 9:03 a.m., United Airlines Flight 175, another Boeing 767, struck the south tower near the 60th floor.

The attacks were soon revealed to be part of a coordinated effort by Islamic terrorists from Saudi Arabia and other Arab nations, financed by Osama bin Laden’s al-Qaeda. They had been living in the U.S. and received flight training and hijacked four planes.

At 9:37 a.m., American Airlines Flight 77 crashed into the Pentagon in Washington, D.C.

The south tower of the World Trade Center collapsed at 9:59 a.m., followed by the north tower at 10:28 a.m., due to the intense heat from the burning jet fuel compromising the structural integrity of the skyscrapers. 

The collapse led to the deaths of nearly 3,000 people, including 343 firefighters, 23 police officers, and 37 Port Authority officers. The attacks, which also included a fourth hijacked plane, United Airlines Flight 93, which crashed in Pennsylvania after passengers attempted to regain control, represented one of the deadliest days in American history and led to significant changes in U.S. domestic and foreign policy.

On this day in history in 1901, President William McKinley was shot twice while shaking hands with the public in New York. 

Although wounded, McKinley stayed conscious and said to “be careful how you tell my wife” and asked his guards not to harm his attacker. Doctors found that one bullet had grazed his sternum and another had penetrated his abdomen. 

Despite initial signs of recovery, McKinley’s condition deteriorated due to gangrene, leading to his death several days later. Vice President Theodore Roosevelt was sworn in as president.

Before McKinley’s assassination, the Secret Service's role primarily involved investigating counterfeit currency and did not include full-time presidential protection.

In response, Congress assigned the Secret Service the permanent duty of protecting the president, a role it continues to fulfill today.

On this day in history in 1836, Sam Houston was elected president of the Republic of Texas, which had recently gained independence from Mexico. 

Houston, who served in the War of 1812 and held political positions in Tennessee, played a crucial role in Texas' independence. He led a decisive victory at the Battle of San Jacinto, and was instrumental in Texas joining the United States in 1845. He served as a senator and governor, though he was later removed for opposing secession.

In a notable incident, Ohio Congressman William Stanbery accused Houston of fraud in a House speech. Two weeks later, Houston confronted Stanbery on Pennsylvania Avenue, calling him a "rascal" and attacking him with a hickory cane from his mentor’s, President Andrew Jackson’s, estate. Stanbery's attempt to defend himself with a pistol failed when it jammed. Houston's assault left Stanbery injured on the street. Houston was found in contempt by Congress and ordered to pay a $500 fine, which he never paid. Jackson later intervened to prevent the fine's collection.

On this day in history in 1886, Apache leader Geronimo surrendered to U.S. troops, marking the end of the Indian Wars in the Southwest. 

Born in present-day Arizona and Mexico, Geronimo grew up amid conflict with settlers encroaching on his tribe's land. After his family was killed by Mexicans, he led raids against both Mexican and American settlers in revenge. After 30 years of fighting to protect his tribe’s land, Geronimo surrendered, making him the last major Native American warrior to do so.

Geronimo was relocated to Florida, then Alabama, and finally to a reservation in Oklahoma Territory, where he adapted to a new life as a farmer and converted to Christianity. He participated in President Theodore Roosevelt’s inaugural parade and died at Fort Sill in 1909.

On this day in history in 31 B.C., Octavian defeated Mark Antony and Cleopatra in the Battle of Actium, which marked the end of the Roman Republic and the beginning of the Roman Empire.

Following the assassination of Julius Caesar, Octavian and Antony vied for control, culminating in the Battle of Actium.

Antony and his lover, Cleopatra, had a larger fleet, but Octavian and his ally, Agrippa, had superior strategic positioning. Cleopatra’s ship withdrew from the battle early on, and Antony followed her, abandoning his forces. This loss of morale led to a swift victory for Octavian and Agrippa.

Months later, Antony and Cleopatra committed suicide. Octavian, who would become Augustus, the first and most successful Roman emperor, reigned until his death in 14 A.D.

On this day in history in 1985, the wreck of the Titanic was found 73 years after it sank.

Found about 400 miles east of Newfoundland and nearly 13,000 feet deep, the ship had broken in two but remained remarkably preserved, surrounded by a wide debris field.

Using a Navy-developed submersible called Argo, the team captured the first images of the ship, beginning with one of its boilers. The discovery revolutionized deep-sea exploration and renewed interest in the Titanic, leading to numerous expeditions, artifact recoveries, and greater understanding of its 1912 sinking.

On this day in history in 1943, the Battle of Kursk, the largest tank battle in warfare history, ends after 50 days. 

The Battle of Kursk, fought in southwestern Russia, was a major clash between Germany and the Soviet Union, culminating in a Soviet victory. This battle, the largest of World War II is often regarded as a key turning point in the war. 

Known for its intense and costly nature, it’s the deadliest armored engagement in history and saw the opening day, July 5, become the most lethal day in aerial warfare. The confrontation began with Germany's Operation Citadel, aimed at encircling the Kursk salient through simultaneous assaults from the north and south. 

The battle was characterized by brutal house-to-house and hand-to-hand combat, involving 6,000 tanks, 2,000,000 troops, and 4,000 aircraft.

On this day in history in 1992, the infamous Ruby Ridge standoff continued. 

Randy Weaver and his family lived atop a mountain in remote Ruby Ridge, Idaho. Weaver was targeted by the government after selling two sawed-off shotguns to an Alcohol, Tobacco, and Firearm (ATF) informant working to catch him. Weaver was let off on bail but failed to appear at court after his defense provided him with the wrong court date. 

After this, ATF handed the case over to the US Marshals, who began surveillance on Weaver and his property by installing various cameras. On August 21, Weaver, his friend, Kevin Harris, his 14 year-old son, Sammy, chased after their dog, Striker, on the family property. They came across an armed, camouflaged man who failed to state that he was a federal agent. The marshal shot and killed the dog before pointing his gun at Sammy, causing Sammy to shoot at the marshal. Sammy was shot in the back while running away from the unmarked agent.

The Weaver family refused to surrender, and the standoff began. The US Marshals then handed the case to the FBI, conveying that a militia group killed a federal agent. Neighbors were evacuated from their homes, roads near Ruby Ridge were closed, and the governor declared a state of emergency. 

The next day, an FBI sniper 200 yards away shot and wounded Weaver and Harris and fatally shot his wife, Vicki Weaver, who was holding their infant daughter.

Nine days later, on August 31, Harris, Weaver, and his three daughters surrendered.

Weaver was initially tried, but was acquitted on all charges except for the original charges of the violation of bail and failure to appear. Weaver filed a civil lawsuit and won over $3 million.

The Korean Axe Murder incident took place a few days before on August 18 when a group of soldiers were pruning a tree planted by Kim Il-Sung. After 15 minutes of trimming, North Korea sent a truckload of soldiers to the site, who swiftly killed the soldiers with the axes used for pruning.

A few days later, Operation Paul Bunyan was carried out to cut down the tree rather than merely prune it. Task Force Vierra, consisting of 813 personnel, included 23 American and South Korean vehicles equipped with chainsaws, two 30-man security platoons, a 64-man South Korean special forces unit, 27 U.S. helicopters, several jets from both America and South Korea, infantry, artillery, and the 71st Air Defense Regiment. The USS Midway was also positioned nearby.

After 42 minutes, the tree was cut down. The soldiers left six feet of the stump deliberately standing as a reminder to North Korea.

On this day in history in 2018, 28-year-old Richard Russell — remembered as "Sky King" — borrowed an airplane from Seattle-Tacoma International Airport for a joyride before crashing into a remote island.

On the evening of August 10th, he gained access to an aircraft and took off smoothly, only drawing attention once fellow employees realized something was wrong.

When the plane eventually ran out of fuel, Russell guided it into Ketron Island. His death was ruled a suicide, possibly linked to past brain injuries from multiple concussions.

Hayden, along with photographer William Jackson and artist Thomas Moran, documented the area’s beauty, providing visual evidence that captured the attention of Congress.

In 1872, Congress passed the Yellowstone Act, setting aside about 2 million acres across Wyoming, Montana, and Idaho as a national park. This law aimed to preserve Yellowstone’s natural wonders for public enjoyment and protection from exploitation.

This sentiment fueled the idea of "no taxation without representation." The Virginia Resolves sparked broader colonial resistance, leading to the Stamp Act Congress in New York, where delegates outlined their objections to the British government.

In response to the protests and pressure, King George III eventually repealed the act in March 1766.

On #ThisDayInHistory in 1917, Germany resumed unrestricted submarine warfare, a policy it had previously suspended due to pressure from the U.S. and neutral countries. 

This policy, initially introduced in 1915, declared the waters around the British Isles a war zone, where German U-boats would attack all merchant ships, including those from neutral nations. The sinking of the British Lusitania, which killed 1,201 people including 128 Americans, led to strong condemnation from the U.S. and a demand for Germany to cease attacking unarmed merchant vessels. 

Afterwards, Germany had limited U-boat attacks, but the navy continued to push for a more aggressive strategy. By early 1917, Germany's military leadership convinced Kaiser Wilhelm to approve resuming unrestricted submarine warfare, believing it could lead to victory by that fall. Despite opposition from the Chancellor, who feared antagonizing the U.S., the kaiser supported the decision, and he announced the resumption of unrestricted U-boat warfare, declaring Germany would "stake everything" and fight to the end.

On #ThisDayInHistory in 1835, Andrew Jackson became the first U.S. president to survive an assassination attempt. 

Richard Lawrence, an unemployed painter, tried to shoot Jackson as he was leaving a funeral at the Capitol. However, his gun misfired. Jackson, 67, responded by attacking Lawrence with his cane. During the struggle, Lawrence drew a second pistol, but it misfired as well. Jackson's aides then subdued Lawrence, leaving the president unharmed but shaken. 

Although Lawrence appeared mentally unstable and had no known political connections, Jackson believed his assassination attempt was orchestrated by his Whig Party opponents, who were at odds with him over his efforts to dismantle the Bank of the United States. 

Despite no evidence to support this claim, Jackson remained paranoid, and his vice president, Martin Van Buren, began carrying two loaded pistols for protection. Lawrence was committed to a mental institution, and later tests showed both of his pistols malfunctioned by chance, with the odds of such a misfire calculated at 1 in 125,000.

After further skirmishes and more crew injuries, the Pueblo was captured and taken to North Korea. The 83-man crew was imprisoned and charged with spying.

The crew was freed in December, walking across the "Bridge of No Return" into South Korea, hailed as heroes.

On #ThisDayInHistory in 2009, Captain Chesley “Sully” Sullenberger landed US Airways Flight 1549 in the Hudson River after taking off from LaGuardia Airport in New York City. 

The flight, with 155 people on board, was en route to Charlotte, North Carolina. Just two minutes into the flight, the aircraft struck a flock of Canada geese, severely damaging both engines and causing a complete loss of thrust. Despite efforts to restart the engines, the plane was unable to regain power.

As the aircraft began losing altitude, Sullenberger quickly realized that returning to LaGuardia was impossible, and nearby airports in New Jersey were also out of reach. With limited options, Sullenberger made the bold decision to attempt a water landing in the Hudson River. He informed passengers over the intercom to “Brace for impact.” The plane landed in the river with the tail section making first contact.

The incident and Sullenberger’s role in it were later dramatized in the 2016 film 𝑆𝑢𝑙𝑙𝑦, directed by Clint Eastwood and starring Tom Hanks as the captain. The event is often cited as a textbook example of effective crisis management and aviation safety.

On #ThisDayInHistory in 1835, President Andrew Jackson succeeded in paying off the U.S. national debt, marking the only time in American history that the debt stood at zero. 

However, this achievement contributed to one of the worst financial crises the country would face. Jackson, influenced by his personal aversion to debt from a failed land deal, opposed the national bank and viewed debt as destructive. During his presidency, he vetoed spending bills, rejected infrastructure projects, and sold government lands to eliminate the debt.

While Jackson's actions initially succeeded in reducing the debt, they led to economic instability. The land sales inflated a real estate bubble, and the dismantling of the national bank resulted in excessive borrowing and spending. These factors, combined with foreign economic downturns, culminated in the Panic of 1837, which plunged the U.S. into a depression and forced the government to resume borrowing. 

The national debt has persisted ever since, growing significantly during the Civil War and World War I. Although many presidents have pledged to eliminate it, the U.S. debt now exceeds $37 trillion.

On #ThisDayInHistory in 1999, the United States officially transferred control of the Panama Canal to Panama, marking the first time the waterway was under Panamanian ownership. 

The 50-mile canal, linking the Atlantic and Pacific Oceans, had been in U.S. hands since its completion in 1914. Over one million ships had passed through the canal by then.

The idea of a canal across Panama dates back to the early 1500s, with various plans proposed but never realized. U.S. interest grew in the mid-1800s, spurred by the California Gold Rush and the need for a shortcut between the oceans.

President Theodore Roosevelt pushed for the project, and in 1903, Panama gained independence from Colombia with U.S. support. The U.S. and Panama signed the Hay-Bunau-Varilla Treaty, giving the U.S. control of the canal zone in exchange for a $10 million payment and annual rent.

In 1977, after decades of Panamanian protests, the Torrijos-Carter Treaties were signed, setting the stage for the 1999 handover. The treaties gave the U.S. the right to defend the canal's neutrality but handed control to Panama.

On #ThisDayInHistory in 1814, the Treaty of Ghent officially ended the War of 1812 between the United States and Great Britain. 

The treaty stipulated that conquered territories would be returned and established commissions to settle the U.S.-Canada border. Despite not addressing the main issues that sparked the war—British interference with American trade and impressment of U.S. sailors—it was seen as a diplomatic victory for the U.S. as it opened the Great Lakes region for expansion.

The war began in June 1812, triggered by British economic blockades, the forced enlistment of American sailors, and British support for Native American attacks on the U.S. frontier. Initial American invasions of Canada were unsuccessful, but the U.S. Navy achieved several victories at sea. In 1814, after Napoleon's defeat, Britain focused more on the war, capturing Washington, D.C., and burning key government buildings. However, the British were repelled at Fort McHenry, inspiring the writing of the "Star-Spangled Banner."

The turning point came in September 1814 when the U.S. won a crucial naval battle at Lake Champlain, forcing British forces to retreat from the northeast. Though news of the treaty’s signing reached the U.S. too late to stop the Battle of New Orleans, where General Andrew Jackson's forces achieved a stunning victory, the simultaneous news of the peace settlement and the triumph at New Orleans boosted American national pride and unity.

On #ThisDayInHistory in 1972, the Apollo lunar program concluded with the safe return of Apollo 17's crew, marking the final manned moon landing. 

Apollo 17 had launched from Cape Canaveral 10 days earlier and its crew, including commander Eugene Cernan, lunar module pilot Harrison Schmitt, and command module pilot Ronald Evans, made significant scientific contributions during their mission. Schmitt, a geologist, became the first scientist-astronaut to land on the moon. The crew spent 75 hours on the lunar surface, conducting three surface excursions in the Lunar Rover and collecting 243 pounds of rock and soil samples.

From 1969 to 1972, NASA successfully carried out six lunar landings, with Apollo 13 being the only mission to be aborted. Apollo 17 remains the most successful and longest manned lunar mission, yielding groundbreaking scientific discoveries and capturing one of the most iconic images of Earth from space.

On #ThisDayInHistory in 1903, near Kitty Hawk, North Carolina, Orville and Wilbur Wright made history with the first successful flight of a self-propelled, heavier-than-air aircraft. 

Orville piloted their gasoline-powered biplane, which flew for 12 seconds and covered 120 feet. The brothers made a total of four flights that day, with Orville and Wilbur alternately piloting the aircraft. The final flight, however, ended in a dramatic mishap. As the brothers were discussing the flight, a strong gust of wind flipped the Wright Flyer several times, causing severe damage. The aircraft was beyond repair, and it was crated and transported back to Dayton, never to fly again.

Over the following years, the Wright brothers continued to refine their aircraft. Their planes could perform complex maneuvers and stay aloft for 39 minutes. They made their first public flights in France and the U.S. Army purchased a plane. The brothers founded the Wright Company to build and market their aircraft. The Wright brothers’ historic 1903 aircraft is now displayed at the National Air and Space Museum in Washington, D.C.

On #ThisDayInHistory in 1773, the Boston Tea Party occurred when a group of Massachusetts colonists disguised as Mohawk Indians boarded three ships in Boston Harbor and dumped 342 chests of tea into the water.

The Boston Tea Party was a protest against the British Parliament's Tea Act, which aimed to save the struggling East India Company by reducing its tax on tea and granting it a monopoly on the American tea trade. Although the Tea Act didn’t raise the price of tea, it allowed the company to undercut smuggled Dutch tea, which angered many colonists who saw it as another form of British control and "taxation without representation."

When the governor refused to allow the tea to be sent back to Britain, Samuel Adams organized the raid with the Sons of Liberty. The destruction of tea, valued at nearly $2 million today, prompted the British to pass the Coercive Acts (Intolerable Acts), which closed Boston's ports and imposed harsher British rule in Massachusetts. This led to the formation of the First Continental Congress, uniting the colonies in opposition to Britain.

Despite the objections, Edward remained determined to marry Simpson, whom he claimed to love. On #ThisDayInHistory in 1941, Japan launched a surprise assault on Pearl Harbor, the U.S. naval base in Hawaii, marking the U.S.'s entry into World War II. 

Tensions between the U.S. and Japan had been escalating for years due to Japan's military expansion in Asia, particularly its invasion of China. By 1941, the U.S. had cut off vital exports to Japan, including oil, and severed diplomatic relations, leading Japan to consider war.

Japan’s military leaders planned the attack on Pearl Harbor as a means to cripple the U.S. Pacific Fleet and secure unchallenged control over Southeast Asia. Despite warnings of possible Japanese aggression, U.S. military leaders did not take sufficient precautions. Tensions in Washington were high, but key warnings failed to reach Pearl Harbor in time.

The attack began at 7:55 AM with a wave of bombers, torpedo planes, and fighters targeting the U.S. fleet. The Japanese destroyed or damaged eight battleships, three cruisers, and nearly 200 aircraft, killing over 2,300 Americans. However, the U.S. aircraft carriers were not in port and survived the attack, which later proved crucial in the Pacific war.

The attack unified the U.S. public, and Congress declared war on Japan the next day with only one dissenting vote. Japan’s miscalculation led to its eventual defeat in the war. Despite the severe damage at Pearl Harbor, the U.S. was able to recover quickly, and Japan’s strategy ultimately backfired, propelling the U.S. into a total war effort that would contribute to the Allied victory but at the cost of 400,000 American lives.

On #ThisDayInHistory in 1945 at 2:10 p.m., five U.S. Navy Avenger torpedo-bombers, part of Flight 19, took off from Ft. Lauderdale Naval Air Station in Florida for a routine training mission and disappeared inside the Bermuda Triangle. 

After completing their initial objective, the flight plan called for them to head east for 67 miles, then north for 73 miles, before returning to the base, totaling 120 miles. 

Two hours into the mission, the flight leader, an experienced pilot, reported compass failures and became disoriented. His instruments malfunctioned, and the other pilots experienced similar issues. Despite attempts to contact land-based radio stations, the squadron's location could not be determined. At 6:20 p.m., the flight leader sent a confused radio message suggesting that the planes may have to ditch due to fuel shortage. By then, radar had located Flight 19 north of the Bahamas, but the search was complicated by poor weather.

A search and rescue Mariner aircraft with a 13-man crew was dispatched at 7:27 p.m., but it disappeared shortly after takeoff. A tanker off the Florida coast reported seeing an explosion. Despite one of the largest air and sea searches in history, no trace of the planes or the crew members was ever found.

The disappearance of Flight 19 and the Mariner contributed to the legend of the Bermuda Triangle, a region in the Atlantic Ocean where ships and aircraft are said to mysteriously vanish.

On #ThisDayInHistory in 1989 during a historic summit off the coast of Malta, President George Bush and Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev make statements suggesting that the Cold War's longstanding tensions are coming to an end. 

The summit, the first between the two leaders, was viewed with cautious optimism by Bush and his advisers, who were eager to build on the arms control progress made during the Reagan administration. Gorbachev, however, was more outspoken, emphasizing his desire for better U.S.-Soviet relations to support his domestic reforms. He declared that the Cold War's defining elements—arms races, mistrust, and ideological conflict—should be left behind. Bush, while more reserved, expressed hope that the U.S. and Soviet Union could usher in a new era of cooperation, particularly in ending the division of Europe.

Despite the optimistic rhetoric, the summit yielded few concrete outcomes. Both leaders agreed to work toward a treaty on nuclear and conventional arms by 1990 and planned a follow-up summit for June 1990 in Washington, D.C.

On #ThisDayInHistory in 2001, Enron Corporation filed for bankruptcy, marking the beginning of one of the largest corporate scandals in U.S. history.

Founded in 1985 through the merger of Houston Natural Gas and Internorth, Enron quickly grew into a major energy-trading company. Under CEO Kenneth Lay, the company reached #7 on Fortune's list of the top 500 U.S. companies by 2000, employing 21,000 people and generating $111 billion in revenue. However, by the end of the year, Enron’s stock price had plummeted from $90.75 in August to just $0.26 by November. As the stock dropped, Lay sold off his shares while encouraging employees to buy more, leading many to lose their retirement savings. The company’s collapse was triggered when a planned $8.4 billion buyout by Dynegy fell through, and Enron filed for bankruptcy.

Enron’s fall was later linked to widespread accounting fraud, where it hid debts and losses through off-the-books partnerships. This prompted investigations by the SEC and Justice Department, revealing that Lay and CEO Jeffrey Skilling had conspired to mislead investors about the company’s financial health. The scandal also implicated Arthur Andersen, Enron’s auditor, which was found guilty of destroying incriminating documents. Although Andersen’s conviction was later overturned, the damage to its reputation led to the firm's downfall.

In 2004, Skilling and Lay were indicted and convicted on multiple charges, including fraud and insider trading. The trial saw former executives, including CFO Andrew Fastow, testify against Lay and Skilling. Fastow had pleaded guilty to conspiracy charges and cooperated with prosecutors. Lay died of heart disease shortly after the verdict, leading to the dismissal of charges against him. Skilling, sentenced to over 24 years in prison, served about 12 years before his release in 2019.

Enron’s collapse cost billions, destroyed thousands of jobs, and became a symbol of corporate fraud, ultimately leading to stricter regulations like the Sarbanes-Oxley Act.

The event became a media sensation, and a year-long legal battle ensued over ownership of the meteorite. Although it was initially sent to the Smithsonian, Alabama congressman Kenneth Roberts intervened, and it was eventually returned to the state.

On #ThisDayInHistory in 1924, the first Macy’s Thanksgiving Day Parade takes place in New York City. 

As the U.S. thrived during the Roaring Twenties, so did Macy's, the iconic New York department store. After going public in 1922, Macy’s expanded rapidly, acquiring competitors and opening new locations. In 1924, Macy's flagship store at Herald Square in Manhattan grew to occupy a full city block, and to mark its debut as "The World’s Largest Store," Macy’s staged a parade on Thanksgiving morning to kick off the holiday shopping season. 

Though it took place on Thanksgiving, the parade was designed to promote Christmas shopping. Inspired by Philadelphia’s Gimbel Brothers’ 1920 parade, Macy’s event featured floats, clowns, animals from Central Park Zoo, and bands, with Santa Claus as the grand finale. 

The parade stretched over six miles, drew thousands of spectators. At its conclusion in front of Macy's, Santa Claus appeared, and the store's famous holiday window display was unveiled. Despite limited media coverage, the parade was so successful that Macy's announced it would be an annual event. Over time, the parade evolved into a major holiday tradition, replacing live animals with character balloons, such as Felix the Cat in 1927, which became the parade's signature feature. 

Today, the Macy's Thanksgiving Day Parade, shortened to 2.5 miles, still draws large crowds and marks the start of the Christmas season in New York.

On #ThisDayInHistory in 1789, the first national Thanksgiving in America takes place. 

The "first" Thanksgiving was held by the Pilgrims in 1621 at Plymouth, where they feasted to thank God for their harvest, inviting the Wampanoag tribe to join them. While this event was not repeated annually, similar observances occurred in other colonies and to celebrate victories in battle. In 1789, President George Washington proclaimed November 26 as a national day of thanksgiving to celebrate the creation of the United States and its new Constitution. Washington personally marked the day by attending church services and making charitable donations.

However, Washington’s proclamation did not establish Thanksgiving as a permanent federal holiday. Although other presidents, like John Adams and James Madison, issued thanksgiving proclamations, it did not become an annual observance until Abraham Lincoln’s presidency during the Civil War.

On #ThisDayInHistory in 1986, it is revealed that the United States had been secretly selling weapons to Iran and giving the funds to the Contras, an anti-communist group in Nicaragua, known as the Iran-Contra Affair. 

The original arms deal, first reported in early November, was meant to secure the release of seven American hostages in Lebanon but violated U.S. policies, including the arms embargo against Iran and President Reagan’s pledge not to negotiate with terrorists. A few weeks later, it was disclosed that the funds from these sales were used to support the Contras, which directly violated the 1982 Boland Amendment prohibiting U.S. aid for overthrowing Nicaragua's government.

A special prosecutor was appointed to investigate, and televised hearings followed, finding that officials attempted to cover up their illegal actions. They concluded that while Reagan and Vice President George Bush didn’t break the law, their actions contributed to a broader effort to deceive Congress and the public.

On #ThisDayInHistory in 1942, Poon Lim, a Chinese steward aboard a British merchant ship, became one of the most famous survivors of a maritime disaster after surviving 133 days at sea when the ship was torpedoed by a German U-boat. 

The ship sank quickly, and Lim was one of the few survivors, managing to escape on a small life raft with little more than some biscuits, a few tins of water, and a flare gun. Stranded in the South Atlantic Ocean, Lim faced extreme challenges, including hunger, dehydration, and brutal exposure to the elements. Using his resourcefulness, he fashioned fishing tools from parts of the raft and caught fish with his bare hands. He also collected rainwater to stay hydrated and used the raft's canopy for shelter from the sun during the day. 

Over the course of his journey, he drifted more than 2,000 miles until he was rescued by a Brazilian fishing boat. By then, he had lost over 40 pounds. Lim was awarded the British Empire Medal for his incredible endurance and determination.

On #ThisDayInHistory in 1974, researchers sent humanity’s first deliberate radio message into space, aimed at potential extraterrestrial life. 

The transmission, broadcast from Puerto Rico’s Arecibo Observatory, marked the completion of an upgrade to the facility's radio telescope. The message, created by astronomers Carl Sagan and Frank Drake, was directed at the M13 star cluster, located about 21,000 light years away. It contained a simple visual message, including the DNA formula, a diagram of the solar system, an image of the Arecibo telescope, and a stick figure of a human.

Though no response came, the researchers, including Cornell University’s Donald Campbell, were not expecting one. The transmission was more symbolic, demonstrating humanity’s technological capability. The Arecibo Observatory, which played a pivotal role in radio astronomy for six decades, tragically collapsed in 2020 due to structural failures. It was decommissioned in 2022, but its legacy in planetary science and space research endures.

On #ThisDayInHistory in 1777, after 16 months of debate, the Continental Congress adopted the Articles of Confederation. 

The Articles created a weak central government, reflecting the Patriots' fear of centralized power. Congress, a single house with one vote per state, could conduct foreign affairs, raise an army, and declare war, but lacked the power to tax. Amendments required unanimous approval from all states. Maryland's ratification in 1781 marked the Articles' official approval by all 13 states.

By 1787, the system was deemed inadequate, prompting the creation of a new constitution. A secret convention convened in Philadelphia to draft a new framework, leading to the U.S. Constitution in 1789, which replaced the Articles of Confederation. This shift marked a transition from rule by a king, to states' sovereignty, and finally to a unified people forming a federal government. This evolution encapsulated the American Revolution's transformation.

On #ThisDayInHistory in 1966, astronaut Buzz Aldrin made history by taking the first-ever space selfie during the Gemini 12 mission, three years before his iconic moon landing. The Gemini 12 mission, aimed at refining techniques for a lunar landing, involved Aldrin and James Lovell performing critical tasks like extravehicular activities (EVAs) and spacecraft docking.

During his spacewalk, Aldrin set up his camera on the hatch of the spacecraft, aiming it at himself and capturing a photo with Earth in the background. This marked the first self-portrait taken in space. Aldrin lifted his helmet visor to allow his face to appear in the shot, despite the challenges posed by the bulky spacesuit and zero-gravity environment.

This historic selfie was made possible by specialized space photography equipment, designed to withstand space's extreme conditions. Aldrin's achievement paved the way for future space selfies, with astronauts like Donald Pettit and Stephen Robinson continuing the trend in the 2000s.

Aldrin’s selfie remains a key milestone in space photography, providing a personal connection to the broader narrative of space exploration.

On #ThisDayInHistory in 1918, World War I ended when Germany, exhausted and on the brink of invasion, signed an armistice with the Allies in Compiégne, France.

The war’s roots trace back to June 28, 1914, when Archduke Franz Ferdinand of Austria-Hungary was assassinated by a Bosnian Serb nationalist. This event escalated tensions between Austria-Hungary and Serbia, with Austria-Hungary blaming the Serbian government for the attack. Russia, allied with Serbia, mobilized its forces, prompting Austria-Hungary to declare war on Serbia on July 28, 1914. The conflict quickly spread as Germany supported Austria-Hungary, while France and Russia aligned against them. Germany's invasion of Belgium led to Britain declaring war on Germany.

The war, initially expected to be short, devolved into a brutal stalemate, especially on the Western Front, where trench warfare caused massive casualties. In 1915, the Allies tried to break the deadlock with a failed invasion of Turkey. By 1916, heavy offensives on the Western Front achieved no decisive results, though Germany had more success in the east, leading to a collapse of the Russian army and the Russian Revolution of 1917. By the end of 1917, the Bolsheviks had taken power and negotiated peace with Germany.

In 1918, the entry of American troops and resources tipped the balance in favor of the Allies. Germany, facing defeat, signed an armistice on November 11. The war, known as the “war to end all wars,” caused unimaginable destruction, resulting in about 9 million military deaths, 21 million wounded, and at least 5 million civilian casualties due to disease, starvation, and exposure. However, the Treaty of Versailles in 1919 imposed harsh terms on Germany, sowing the seeds for future conflict and leading to World War II.

On #ThisDayInHistory in 1989, East German officials opened the Berlin Wall, allowing free travel between East and West Berlin. The next day, jubilant crowds began tearing the wall down. 

This marked the collapse of one of the Cold War's most infamous symbols, as the wall's destruction was quickly followed by souvenir hunters collecting pieces of rubble. The decision to open the wall was influenced by Hungary's recent move to open its border with Austria, allowing East Germans to bypass the Berlin Wall entirely and escape to the West. 

The fall of the wall also reflected broader political shifts in East Germany, where the communist regime was losing power and calls for democratic reforms grew louder. The event had a significant impact on U.S. President George Bush and his advisors, who, after watching the celebrations on television, grew more convinced that Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev’s reformist stance was genuine. Unlike past Soviet crackdowns in Hungary (1956) and Czechoslovakia (1968), Gorbachev supported the changes in East Germany, signaling a shift in Soviet policy. The fall of the Berlin Wall was a key moment in the Cold War's decline.

On #ThisDayInHistory in 1895, physicist Wilhelm Conrad Röntgen discovered X-rays while experimenting with cathode rays in his lab in Germany. 

Noticing a glow from a nearby screen, he identified the unknown rays and named them X-rays. These electromagnetic waves, much shorter than visible light, could penetrate soft tissue but were blocked by denser materials like bone. Röntgen's discovery revolutionized medicine by allowing doctors to view the inside of the human body without surgery. X-rays were first used in military medicine during the Balkan War of 1897 to locate bullets and fractures.

Though initially seen as harmless, the dangers of X-ray radiation became apparent in the early 1900s after reports of burns and skin damage, and the death of Thomas Edison's assistant from cancer. Despite these risks, X-rays were used in various consumer products, like shoe-fitting fluoroscopes, until the 1950s, when their dangers were better understood. Röntgen, who received the first Nobel Prize in Physics in 1901 for his discovery, never patented X-rays. Today, X-ray technology is widely used in medicine, security, and materials testing.

On #ThisDayInHistory in 2000, the U.S. presidential election was ruled inconclusive as only 537 votes in Florida separated Al Gore and George W. Bush.

The election was a tumultuous process, starting with confusion on election night as networks first declared Florida for Gore, then for Bush, and back again, before Gore retracted his concession.

Despite Gore winning the popular vote by over 500,000 votes, the Electoral College ultimately decided the outcome. The recounts and legal challenges in Florida became a national spectacle, with terms like "hanging chads" and "dimpled chads" becoming widely recognized. The controversial butterfly ballot design in Florida, which led to misvotes, compounded the problem.

The recount process was marred by inconsistent standards and legal battles, culminating in a decision by the U.S. Supreme Court. The Court ruled 7-2 that the recount violated constitutional standards for consistency, and by a 5-4 vote, stopped the recount due to time constraints, effectively awarding Florida—and thus the presidency—to Bush.

The ruling, which divided along ideological lines, remains one of the most controversial in American history. Bush won the election despite losing the popular vote, making him the first president since 1888 to do so.

On #ThisDayInHistory in 1940, Franklin D. Roosevelt was elected to an unprecedented third term as President of the United States, becoming the first U.S. president in history to win more than two terms in office. 

Roosevelt, who had already served as president for nearly eight years, defeated his Republican opponent by a wide margin, securing 84.5% of the electoral vote. His victory reflected the continued public support for his leadership during one of the most challenging periods in American history.

FDR's presidency was marked by bold and transformative actions aimed at addressing the Great Depression and guiding the nation through the early years of World War II. Under his New Deal programs, Roosevelt introduced groundbreaking economic reforms, including Social Security, labor rights protections, and public works projects, which sought to provide relief, recovery, and reform to a country devastated by economic collapse.

As he campaigned for his third term in 1940, Roosevelt was also faced with the growing threat of global conflict. World War II was already raging in Europe, and Roosevelt had begun to prepare the U.S. for its eventual involvement, despite widespread isolationist sentiment at home.

Roosevelt's third term would prove to be pivotal, as the United States officially entered World War II in December 1941, following the Japanese attack on Pearl Harbor. Roosevelt's leadership during the war would shape not only the future of the United States but also the world order in the post-war era.

FDR's election for a third term marked a significant moment in U.S. history, signaling the nation's confidence in his ability to navigate turbulent times. His continued presidency, however, also sparked debates about presidential term limits, leading to the eventual passage of the 22nd Amendment in 1951, which formally restricted U.S. presidents to two terms in office.

On #ThisDayInHistory in 1847, The Hughes Flying Boat, also known as the "Spruce Goose," flies for the first and last time. 

Howard Hughes, a successful Hollywood producer, founded the Hughes Aircraft Company in 1932 and made several aviation records, including a transcontinental flight in 1937 and a round-the-world trip in 1938. After the U.S. entered World War II, Hughes was commissioned to develop the H-4 flying boat. Originally conceived by Henry Kaiser, the project fell to Hughes due to Kaiser’s withdrawal. With steel in short supply, the aircraft was primarily made of wood, which led to its nickname. It was intended to transport over 700 troops.

The development cost $23 million and took so long that the war ended before its completion in 1946. Critics questioned its viability, prompting Congress to require a demonstration of airworthiness. Hughes surprised thousands of spectators by flying the Spruce Goose for a mile over Long Beach Harbor.

Despite this successful flight, the Spruce Goose never entered production due to concerns about its wooden structure. After becoming increasingly reclusive, Hughes maintained the aircraft in a climate-controlled hangar until his death in 1976. The Spruce Goose is now displayed at the Evergreen Aviation Museum in McMinnville, Oregon.

On #ThisDayInHistory in 1955, a bomb aboard United Airlines Flight 629 kills 44 people. 

The flight took off from Denver, bound for Portland. Just 11 minutes into the flight, the plane crashed near Longmont, killing all 39 passengers and five crew members. Initial investigations revealed signs of an explosion; wreckage analysis showed damage to the fuselage, and eyewitnesses reported seeing fireballs in the sky and on the ground.

As the investigation progressed, it became clear that the crash was not due to mechanical failure or pilot error. The FBI was called in to pursue a criminal investigation. A crucial lead emerged when investigators found that passenger Daisie E. King had been carrying newspaper clippings concerning her son, Jack Gilbert Graham, who had a criminal history involving forgery and was on a local most-wanted list. Notably, Graham was the beneficiary of at least $37,500 in life insurance policies on his mother, and there were reports of strained relations between them.

As the investigation deepened, FBI agents discovered detonating wire at Graham's residence. This prompted further interrogation, during which Graham confessed to his heinous act: he had constructed a homemade bomb using 25 sticks of dynamite, hidden it in his mother’s luggage, and set it to explode after a timed delay, having purchased a 60-minute timing device shortly before the flight.

Graham's motives were rooted in financial gain; in addition to the life insurance policies, he stood to inherit a significant sum upon his mother's death. Testimonies revealed frequent arguments between them, supporting the notion of a strained relationship leading to Graham's desperate act.

Ultimately, he was found guilty and sentenced to death, with his execution taking place in January 1957.

One lingering question about the case was why Graham was only charged with the murder of his mother despite the loss of 44 lives. Legal experts noted that this strategy was likely the most straightforward route to secure a death penalty conviction, as specific laws governing airline bombings had yet to be established.

On #ThisDayInHistory in 100 BC, the ancient Celtic festival of Samhain, celebrated on to mark the end of the harvest and the onset of winter, began. 

The Celts, who lived in what is now Ireland, the UK, and northern France, believed this night blurred the line between the living and the dead. They lit bonfires, wore costumes, and performed rituals to ward off spirits and seek guidance from Druids, the Celtic priests.

In the 8th century, Pope Gregory III established November 1 as All Saints Day, which integrated elements of Samhain, leading to the evening before being known as All Hallows Eve, or Halloween. By the 9th century, as Christianity spread, it further absorbed Celtic traditions, and November 2 became All Souls’ Day, honoring the dead in ways similar to Samhain.

While Halloween celebrations were limited in Puritan New England due to strict religious beliefs, they thrived in southern colonies where communal harvest celebrations emerged. With the arrival of Irish immigrants in the late 19th century, Halloween gained national popularity. These immigrants brought customs like dressing in costumes, where children went door-to-door asking for food, evolving into the modern trick-or-treating tradition.

By the late 1800s, there was a concerted effort in America to reshape Halloween into a community-focused holiday, emphasizing neighborly gatherings over its darker roots. This led to the rise of Halloween parties, featuring games, seasonal foods, and festive costumes. Newspapers and community leaders advocated for removing frightening elements, resulting in a Halloween that lost much of its superstitious and religious connotations by the early 20th century, focusing instead on fun and community spirit.

Following Yuri Gagarin's historic flight in 1961, Glenn's Friendship 7 mission made him a national hero as it orbited the Earth three times. He was celebrated with a visit from President Kennedy and a ticker-tape parade.

On #ThisDayInHistory in 1929, known as Black Thursday, the U.S. stock market experienced a dramatic decline, marking the beginning of a catastrophic financial crisis that contributed to the Great Depression. 

This event followed a period of significant economic optimism during the Roaring Twenties, characterized by rising stock prices and rampant speculation. The crisis began on October 23, when stock prices fell 4.6%, leading to widespread panic among investors. On Black Thursday, an unprecedented 12.9 million shares were traded, far exceeding previous records. This surge overwhelmed stockbrokers, causing delays and inaccuracies in trade reports, which intensified the sense of chaos. In response to the turmoil, police were dispatched to the New York Stock Exchange to maintain order, while Wall Street executives attempted to reassure the public.

Leading up to the crash, many stocks were purchased on margin, meaning investors borrowed money to buy shares, which left them vulnerable to sudden price drops. While some economists had raised alarms about the market's sustainability, many investors remained hopeful, believing prices would continue to rise.

In a bid to stabilize the market, major banks and investment firms intervened by purchasing large blocks of stocks. Initially, this action seemed to quell the panic, as the market closed only slightly down for the day. However, the temporary boost did little to restore confidence. On the following days, known as Black Monday and Black Tuesday, stock prices plummeted further.

The aftermath of Black Thursday triggered a ripple effect across the economy, contributing to decreased manufacturing and rising unemployment. While the crash was a pivotal moment, economists continue to debate whether it was a direct cause of the Great Depression or a symptom of underlying economic weaknesses.

On #ThisDayInHistory in 1797, the USS Constitution is launched in the Boston Harbor.

The USS Constitution, known as Old Ironsides, is a historic three-masted wooden frigate of the U.S. Navy and the oldest commissioned naval warship still afloat. Launched in 1797, she was one of six frigates built under the Naval Act of 1794 to serve as a capital ship for the young Navy. Constructed in a Boston shipyard, her early missions included protecting American merchant ships during the Quasi-War with France and combating Barbary pirates.

Most famous for her role in the War of 1812, the Constitution captured numerous merchant ships and defeated five British warships, earning her the nickname "Old Ironsides." After the war, she served in various capacities, including as a flagship in the Mediterranean and as a training ship during the Civil War. Notably, she circled the globe in the 1840s.

Retired from active duty in 1881, the Constitution became a museum ship in 1907. She completed a national tour in 1934 and sailed under her own power for her bicentennial in 1997 and again in 2012 to commemorate her victory over the Guerriere.

Today, the Constitution's mission is to educate the public about the Navy's role in history through outreach, demonstrations, and participation in events. She is crewed by active-duty Navy personnel, who conduct tours and ceremonies while she is docked at the Charlestown Navy Yard in Boston.

On #ThisDayInHistory in 1867, the U.S. officially acquired Alaska from Russia for $7.2 million, equivalent to less than two cents per acre. 

The territory, inhabited by Indigenous peoples for thousands of years, spanned 586,412 square miles—about twice the size of Texas—and was promoted by Secretary of State William Henry Seward.

Russia sought to sell the remote territory to avoid losing it in a potential conflict with Great Britain. Despite public skepticism, which led to derisive names like “Seward’s Folly,” negotiations between Seward and Russian minister Eduard de Stoeckl began in March 1867. Public disapproval was partly fueled by President Andrew Johnson's unpopularity, especially following his impeachment in 1868. Ultimately, Congress approved the purchase.

Alaska was under U.S. Army control until June 1877, after which it was briefly governed by the Treasury Department and various military authorities. Most Russians in the territory returned to Russia after the sale, and those who stayed had the option to apply for U.S. citizenship within three years, though most eventually departed. A civil government was established in May 1884 when Alaska became a district.

Public sentiment shifted positively after gold was discovered in Nome, Alaska, in 1899, igniting a gold rush. Alaska became the 49th state on January 3, 1959, and is now known for its rich natural resources, supplying a significant portion of the U.S. oil and seafood.

On #ThisDayInHistory in 1978, President Jimmy Carter officially restores the full citizenship rights of Jefferson Davis, the former president of the Confederacy, effectively resolving a century-long debate. 

Davis is primarily remembered alongside General Robert E. Lee, who had his citizenship restored by Congress in 1976. The congressional resolution acknowledged Davis's significant contributions, noting his service as a soldier, U.S. Congressman, and Secretary of War. It stated that restoring his citizenship completed the reconciliation process that followed the Civil War, emphasizing the need to reunite the nation after its divisive conflict.

Davis's path to citizenship restoration was complicated by the 14th Amendment, which barred former Confederates from holding public office unless Congress intervened. Although he was indicted for treason after the war, the charges were ultimately dismissed when President Andrew Johnson issued a general pardon in 1868. This pardon restored civil rights but did not grant the right to hold office.

In the 1870s, discussions arose about potentially allowing Davis to run for Senate, but he was specifically excluded from an 1876 universal amnesty bill that restored citizenship rights to most former Confederates. Davis’s refusal to seek a pardon was rooted in his belief that he had not acted wrongfully, famously stating, “repentance must precede the right of pardon.”

Before his leadership in the Confederacy, Davis was a highly respected U.S. senator from Mississippi. His resignation speech in 1861, delivered as Mississippi prepared to secede, was a dramatic moment in the lead-up to the Civil War. In it, he expressed hope for peaceful relations while asserting the right to leave the Union, evoking strong emotions among his colleagues.

The restoration of Davis's citizenship by Carter not only acknowledged his historical role but also highlighted the ongoing complexities of reconciling the legacies of the Civil War and its leaders in American history.

On #ThisDayInHistory in 1962, the Cuban Missile Crisis begins, marking a critical confrontation between the U.S. and the Soviet Union, bringing the two superpowers closest to nuclear war during the Cold War. 

Following the failed Bay of Pigs invasion, Soviet Premier Nikita Khrushchev secretly arranged to place nuclear missiles in Cuba to deter future attacks. U.S. surveillance revealed the missile sites in October, prompting President Kennedy to convene his advisers.

Kennedy decided on a naval "quarantine" of Cuba, publicly warning that any missile launched from Cuba would be treated as an attack by the Soviet Union. As tensions escalated, U.S. forces were placed on high alert. A few weeks later, a potential diplomatic solution emerged when a Soviet agent proposed removing missiles in exchange for a U.S. non-invasion promise. However, Khrushchev later insisted that the U.S. remove its missiles from Turkey.

Amid increasing tensions, including the shooting down of a U-2 jet, Kennedy chose to respond to the initial Soviet message, proposing a supervised removal of missiles from Cuba. This was coupled with a secret indication of U.S. plans to remove missiles from Turkey. On October 28, Khrushchev announced the dismantling of Soviet missiles in Cuba, effectively ending the crisis.

The crisis not only bolstered Kennedy's standing but also highlighted communication failures between the two nations, leading to the establishment of a direct communication line known as the "Hotline" and a reconsideration of nuclear arms policies, paving the way for future arms control agreements.

On this day in 1982, President Ronald Reagan declared illicit drugs a significant threat to U.S. national security. 

The phrase "war on drugs" was initially popularized by Richard Nixon in 1971, but the origins of drug policy in the U.S. can be traced back to the Harrison Narcotics Tax Act of 1914 and the establishment of the Federal Bureau of Narcotics in 1930, reflecting a long history of drug regulation.

In a speech at the Justice Department, Reagan likened his administration’s commitment to combating drug use and trafficking to the determination shown by the French army during the Battle of Verdun in World War I, stressing that challenges could be overcome with resolve. He quoted a French soldier, asserting, “There are no impossible situations. There are only people who think they’re impossible.”

First Lady Nancy Reagan played a crucial role in spreading the anti-drug message, actively touring elementary schools to educate children about the dangers of drug use. During one visit, when a fourth grader at Longfellow Elementary School in Oakland, California, asked how to respond if offered drugs, she famously replied, “Just say no,” making the phrase a cultural touchstone.

In 1988, Reagan established the Office of National Drug Control Policy (ONDCP) to coordinate drug-related initiatives across various government sectors, including legislation, security, and health policy. The media dubbed its directors “drug czars,” reflecting the growing focus on a centralized approach to drug control. In 1993, President Bill Clinton elevated the position to Cabinet-level status, highlighting the ongoing commitment to addressing drug issues at the highest levels of government.

Reagan’s efforts marked a significant escalation in the War on Drugs, leading to increased funding for drug enforcement and harsher penalties for drug offenses, which contributed to a dramatic rise in incarceration rates for nonviolent drug crimes. This intensified focus on drug policy would have lasting implications for law enforcement and communities across the nation.

On #ThisDayInHistory in 1992, Deion Sanders attempted to make sports history by playing in both the NFL and MLB on the same day. 

“Prime Time” began his day with the Atlanta Falcons facing the Miami Dolphins at the Orange Bowl, where they lost 21-17. In that game, Sanders showcased his versatility by returning two kicks, a punt, and catching a nine-yard pass, all while contributing to a defense tasked with containing the legendary Dan Marino.

Immediately after the game, Sanders flew to Pittsburgh for Game 5 of the 1992 NLCS with the Atlanta Braves. He arrived still in his Falcons gear, unprepared for the 53-degree weather. Although he did not see any action in the Braves' 7-1 defeat to the Pirates, his mere presence was historic; had he played, he would have been the first athlete to compete in two major American professional sports on the same day.

A week later, Sanders had another opportunity to make history, with the Falcons facing the 49ers and the Braves hosting the Blue Jays for Game 2 of the World Series. However, he opted to remain in Atlanta, starting in left field. He recorded one hit and two walks in a closely contested 5-4 loss to the Blue Jays. While his attempts to play in both leagues on the same day didn’t succeed, Sanders’s dual-sport aspirations left a lasting mark on sports history.

On #ThisDayInHistory in 1936, the Hoover Dam began transmitting electricity generated by the Colorado River across 266 miles to power Los Angeles. 

Originally named Boulder Dam, construction commenced under President Hoover's administration but was completed during Roosevelt's presidency, which ultimately renamed it in Hoover's honor. When finished in 1935, the dam stood as the tallest in the world and became a powerful symbol of the federal government's commitment to large-scale reclamation projects aimed at transforming the arid West.

On #ThisDayInHistory in 1957, the Space Age begins with the launch of Sputnik, the first artificial satellite, by the Soviet Union. 

The satellite launched from the Tyuratam launch base in Kazakhstan. Weighing 184 pounds and measuring 22 inches in diameter, Sputnik orbited Earth every hour and 36 minutes at a speed of 18,000 miles per hour. It transmitted radio signals that could be received by amateur radio operators in the U.S., sparking both fascination and concern over Soviet technological advancements.

Launched to coincide with the International Geophysical Year, Sputnik’s success prompted fears in the U.S. about potential military applications of Soviet rocket technology, especially as it was significantly larger than the planned U.S. satellite, Explorer, which launched in January of 1958. The launch of Sputnik marked the beginning of the space race, as the U.S. government and military scrambled to catch up.

In the following years, the Soviet Union achieved several space milestones, including the first living being in orbit, the first human in space, and numerous other firsts. However, the U.S. made a significant leap in 1969 with the Apollo 11 mission, successfully landing astronauts on the moon.

On #ThisDayInHistory in 1890, Yosemite National Park is established. 

Renowned for its natural wonders like Half Dome and giant sequoias, this achievement was largely driven by environmental advocate John Muir and others, with support from President Benjamin Harrison. 

The park's creation followed a history of Native American habitation disrupted by the 1849 gold rush, which led to ecological damage and increased tourism. President Abraham Lincoln designated Yosemite Valley and the Mariposa Grove as a public trust to protect them from exploitation, laying the groundwork for future national parks.

Muir and fellow advocate Robert Underwood Johnson pushed for national park status to protect the meadows around Yosemite from overgrazing by sheep. Their efforts resulted in the designation of over 1,500 square miles as Yosemite National Park, the third national park in the U.S. Federal jurisdiction eventually extended to Yosemite Valley and Mariposa Grove. Ansel Adams later captured the park's beauty through iconic black-and-white photographs. 

Today, Yosemite attracts over 3 million visitors each year, who come to explore its breathtaking features, including Yosemite Falls, Half Dome, El Capitan, and the giant sequoia groves.

On #ThisDayInHistory in 1982, the Tylenol scare began when seven Chicago residents died over the course of a few days after taking cyanide-laced extra-strength Tylenol capsules. 

After initial investigations of the deaths of the victims, doctors determined cyanide contamination, leading Johnson & Johnson to issue a historic recall of 31 million bottles. The cyanide had not originated in the company's facilities; rather, someone had likely tampered with the bottles after purchasing them.

Police used bullhorns throughout the streets of Chicago to urge residents to dispose of any Tylenol in their homes. Public health officials distributed flyers, and stores removed all Tylenol products from their shelves.

James Lewis, who claimed to be the Tylenol killer, sent a letter to Johnson & Johnson demanding $1 million to stop the poisonings. However, after an extensive investigation, authorities found no connection between him and the Chicago incidents. He was charged with extortion and sentenced to 20 years in prison but was released in 1995 after serving 13 years.

In response to the crisis, Tylenol introduced tamper-evident seals and solid pills, making contamination more difficult. The “Tylenol bill” passed in 1983 made tampering with consumer products a federal offense. Johnson & Johnson's handling of the situation is considered a model for crisis management, and their stock rebounded within two months of the scare.

On #ThisDayInHistory in 1964, the Warren Commission, tasked with investigating the assassination of President Kennedy by Lee Harvey Oswald, releases a report, concluding that Oswald acted as a "lone gunman.”

President Kennedy was shot and killed while traveling in an open-top limousine during a motorcade in Dallas in 1963.

Less than an hour after the shooting, Lee Harvey Oswald, a former Marine employed at the Texas School Book Depository, shot a police officer who questioned him. He was arrested in a movie theater shortly after. Oswald was charged with the murders of Kennedy and Officer J.D. Tippit.

The following day, as Oswald was being transferred from the Dallas police headquarters, Jack Ruby shot him with a concealed revolver in front of police and reporters. Ruby, a nightclub owner with ties to organized crime, claimed he acted out of anger over Kennedy’s assassination.

As Oswald was killed shortly after assassinating Kennedy, his motive remained unclear. In response, President Johnson established the Warren Commission to investigate the assassination. Led by Chief Justice Earl Warren, the commission included U.S. senators, representatives, a former CIA director, and a former World Bank president.

Over nearly a year, the commission examined reports from the FBI, Secret Service, and others, reviewed Oswald’s background, and interviewed hundreds of witnesses while visiting the assassination site in Dallas. 

The commission released an 888-page report concluding that Oswald fired three shots from a sixth-floor window of the Texas School Book Depository, killing Kennedy and injuring Governor Connally. While the report detailed Oswald’s life and connections, it did not explore his motives. It also criticized the Secret Service for inadequate security during Kennedy’s Dallas visit and stated that Jack Ruby acted alone in killing Oswald.

This finding did not satisfy many witnesses and researchers who found inconsistencies in the report. Various conspiracy theories emerged, implicating entities like the Cuban and Soviet governments, organized crime, the FBI, CIA, and even Vice President Johnson. Critics pointed to ballistics evidence and a home movie that seemed to challenge the claim that three bullets from Oswald caused Kennedy's fatal wounds and Connally's injuries.

In the late 1970s, the House Select Committee on Assassinations (HSCA) conducted a new investigation. Their report supported the Warren Commission's finding that Oswald fired two bullets but also suggested a high probability of a second gunman and an unspecified conspiracy behind the assassination. Both reports remain subjects of debate.

The extensive documentation from the Warren Commission is housed in the National Archives, with much available to the public; however, access to Kennedy’s autopsy records is highly restricted, requiring special permission or affiliation with a presidential or congressional commission.

On #ThisDayInHistory in 1960, the first televised debate between major party presidential candidates took place in U.S. history. 

Democratic Senator John F. Kennedy and Republican Vice President Richard Nixon debated U.S. domestic issues in a Chicago studio. Kennedy recognized that the debates could significantly boost his campaign. The 43-year-old Massachusetts senator, who had risen from relative obscurity to become the Democratic nominee, faced challenges regarding his perceived inexperience as a leader. In preparation, he reviewed key facts and napped and tanned before the debate. He appeared well-rested and fit, a fact later acknowledged by Richard Nixon.

In contrast, Nixon was exhausted and unwell. The sitting Vice President had been campaigning vigorously across all 50 states and had recently spent time in the hospital due to a knee injury and subsequent infection. Arriving at the debate with a fever and in pain, he looked haggard, with debate producer Don Hewitt remarking that he appeared "like death warmed over." Despite his condition, Nixon chose to proceed with the debate, fearing that withdrawing would make him seem cowardly.

Interestingly, listeners on the radio believed Nixon won the presidential debate, while viewers who watched it thought Kennedy was the victor.

Although Nixon performed better in the second and third debates, Kennedy ultimately won the election, securing 49.7% of the popular vote against Nixon's 49.6%, making it one of the closest elections in U.S. history.

Nixon returned to presidential politics in 1968 but chose not to debate his opponent, similar to Lyndon Johnson in 1964. Televised debates resumed in 1976 and have been a staple of presidential campaigns ever since.

On #ThisDayInHistory in 1939, Andorra and Germany sign a peace treaty to end World War I, as Andorra was forgotten in the 1918 Treaty of Versailles. 

Andorra is a small European nation located between France and Spain, covering less than 200 square miles and home to just 85,000 people. 

During WWI, Andorra symbolically declared war on Germany but never sent troops, as it has no standing army. When the Treaty of Versailles was signed, Andorra wasn't invited, leaving it in a state of "belligerence" without active conflict.

Despite remaining technically at war, Andorra didn't participate in WWII, likely due to its lack of military capability and its role as a smuggling route. The "war" became largely forgotten, until Andorra finally made peace with Germany in 1939, marking the official end of World War I for everyone just as World War II was kicking off.
